def horiz_concat_df(dict_of_df, head=None):
    """
    Horizontally concatenante multiple DataFrames for easier visualization. 
    Each DataFrame must have the same columns.
    """
    df = pd.concat([df.reset_index(drop=True) for df in dict_of_df.values()], axis=1, keys=dict_of_df.keys())
    if head is None:
        return df
    return df.head(head)

After spotting a pattern, I used a regular expression to convert this messy HTML snippet into something more readable. Something Like: <a href="http://twitter.com/download/iphone" rel="nofollow">Twitter for iPhone</a> as Twitter for iPhone.

Patterns¶

I used the Python re library to cleanup the above test string. Below, I wrote a regular expression that would match the HTML tag and assign it to the variable a_pattern. We then use the re.sub function to substitute anything that matches the pattern with an empty string "".

An HTML tag is defined as a < character followed by zero or more non-> characters, followed by a > character. That is, <a> and </a> are both considered separate HTML tags.

In [12]:
a_pattern = r"<[^>]*>"
test_str = '<a href="http://twitter.com/download/iphone" rel="nofollow">Twitter for iPhone</a>'
re.sub(a_pattern, "", test_str)
Out[12]:
'Twitter for iPhone'

Capture¶

Rather than writing a regular expression to detect and remove the HTML tags I could instead write a regular expression to capture the device name between the angle brackets. Here I used capturing groups by placing parenthesis around the part of the regular expression I wanted to return. For example, to capture the 21 in the string 08/21/83 we could use the pattern r"08/(..)/83".

In [14]:
b_pattern = r">([^>]*)<"
test_str = '<a href="http://twitter.com/download/iphone" rel="nofollow">Twitter for iPhone</a>'
re.findall(b_pattern, test_str)
Out[14]:
['Twitter for iPhone']

Extract¶

Using Series.str.extract, added a new column called "device" to all of the DataFrames in tweets containing just the text describing the device (without the HTML tags).

In [16]:
def add_device(df):
    df["device"] = df["source"].str.extract(b_pattern)
    return df
In [17]:
tweets = {k: add_device(v) for k, v in tweets.items()}

Frequency¶

To examine the most frequently used devices by each individual, I implemented the most_freq function that takes in a Series and returns a new Series containing the k most commonly occurring entries in the first series, where the values are the counts of the entries and the indices are the entries themselves.

For example:

most_freq(pd.Series(["A", "B", "A", "C", "B", "A"]), k=2)

returns:

A    3
B    2
dtype: int64
In [19]:
def most_freq(series, k = 5):
    return series.value_counts().nlargest(k)

When?¶

Once that I explored the sources of each of the tweets, I performed some time series analysis. A look into the temporal aspect of the data could reveal insights about how a user spends their day, when they eat and sleep, etc. In this section, I focused on the time at which each tweet was posted.

By Hour¶

The following function add_hour takes in a tweets dataframe df, and two column names time_col and result_col. The function uses the timestamps in the time_col column to store in a new column result_col the computed hour of the day as a floating point number according to the formula:

$$ \text{hour} + \frac{\text{minute}}{60} + \frac{\text{second}}{60^{2}} $$

The below code calls the add_hour function and updates each tweets dataframe by using the created_at timestamp column to calculate and store the hour column.

In [23]:
def add_hour(df, time_col, result_col):
    df[result_col] = df[time_col].dt.hour + df[time_col].dt.minute / 60 + df[time_col].dt.second / 60 ** 2
    return df

tweets = {handle: add_hour(df, "created_at", "hour") for handle, df in tweets.items()}

With the new hour column, I could take a look at the distribution of tweets for each user by time of day. The following cell helps create a density plot on the number of tweets based on the hour they are posted.

The function bin_df takes in a dataframe, an array of bins, and a column name; it bins the the values in the specified column, returning a dataframe with the bin lower bound and the number of elements in the bin. This function uses pd.cut, a pandas utility for binning numerical values that I found helpful.

In [25]:
def bin_df(df, bins, colname):
    binned = pd.cut(df[colname], bins).value_counts().sort_index()
    return pd.DataFrame({"counts": binned, "bin": bins[:-1]})

hour_bins = np.arange(0, 24.5, .5)
binned_hours = {handle: bin_df(df, hour_bins, "hour") for handle, df in tweets.items()}

make_line_plot(binned_hours, "bin", "counts", title="Distribution of Tweets by Time of Day",
               xlabel="Hour", ylabel="Number of Tweets")

The following function convert_timezone takes in a tweets dataframe df and a timezone new_tz and adds a new column converted_time that has the adjusted created_at timestamp for each tweet. def convert_timezone(df, new_tz):
    df["converted_time"] = df["created_at"].dt.tz_convert(new_tz)
    return df

timezones = {"AOC": "EST", "Cristiano": "Europe/Lisbon", "elonmusk": "America/Los_Angeles"}

tweets = {handle: convert_timezone(df, tz) for (handle, df), tz in zip(tweets.items(), timezones.values())}

Sentiment¶

In the past few sections, I explored the sources of the tweets and when they are posted. Although on their own, they might not seem particularly intricate, combined with the power of regular expressions, they could actually help us infer a lot about the users. In this section, I continued building on the past analysis and specifically looking at the sentiment of each tweet -- this would lead to a much more direct and detailed understanding of how the users view certain subjects and people.


But wait, how can we actually measure the sentiment of each tweet? In this case, I could use the words in the text of a tweet for our calculation! For example, the word "love" within the sentence "I love America!" has a positive sentiment, whereas the word "hate" within the sentence "I hate taxes!" has a negative sentiment. In addition, some words have stronger positive / negative sentiment than others: "I love America." is more positive than "I like America."

I made use of the VADER (Valence Aware Dictionary and sEntiment Reasoner) lexicon to analyze the sentiment of AOC's tweets. VADER is a lexicon and rule-based sentiment analysis tool that is specifically attuned to sentiments expressed in social media which is great for this usage.



The VADER lexicon gives the sentiment of individual words. The following cell to show the first few rows of the lexicon:

As you can see, the lexicon contains emojis too! Each row contains a word and the polarity of that word, measuring how positive or negative the word is.

VADER Sentiment Analysis¶

VADER is a tool that can quantitatively describe the polarity or "sentiment" of a word.

VADER doesn't "read" sentences, but works by parsing sentences into words, assigning a preset generalized score from their testing sets to each word separately.

VADER relies on humans to stabilize its scoring. The creators use Amazon Mechanical Turk, a crowdsourcing survey platform, to train its model. Its training data consists of a small corpus of tweets, New York Times editorials and news articles, Rotten Tomatoes reviews, and Amazon product reviews, tokenized using the natural language toolkit (NLTK). Each word in each dataset was reviewed and rated by at least 20 trained individuals who had signed up to work on these tasks through Mechanical Turk.

I first loaded in the data containing all the sentiments. I Read vader_lexicon.txt into a dataframe called sent. The index of the dataframe as the words in the lexicon and was named token. sent has one column named polarity, storing the polarity of each word.

More Patterns¶

Before further analysis, I needed some more tools that could help me extract the necessary information and clean the data.

The following regular expressions helped me match part of a tweet that I either (i) wanted to remove or (ii) was interested in learning more about.

Punctuation¶

Assigning a regular expression to a new variable punct_re that captures all of the punctuations within a tweet. I considered punctuation to be any non-word, non-whitespace character.

A word character is any character that is alphanumeric or an underscore. A whitespace character is any character that is a space, a tab, a new line, or a carriage return.

In [33]:
punct_re = r'\W'

re.sub(punct_re, " ", tweets["AOC"].iloc[0]["full_text"])
Out[33]:
'RT  RepEscobar  Our country has the moral obligation and responsibility to reunite every single family separated at the southern border   T '

Mentions¶

Assigning a regular expression to a new variable mentions_re that matches any mention in a tweet. The regular expression uses a capturing group to extract the user's username in a mention.

In [35]:
mentions_re = r"@(\w+)"

re.findall(mentions_re, tweets["AOC"].iloc[0]["full_text"])
Out[35]:
['RepEscobar']


Tweet Sentiments and User Mentions¶

As seen in the previous part of this project, there are actually a lot of interesting components that I could extract out of a tweet for further analysis. For the rest however, I focused on one particular case: the sentiment of each tweet in relation to the users mentioned within it.

To calculate the sentiments for a sentence, I followed this procedure:

  1. Removed the punctuation from each tweet so I could analyze the words.
  2. For each tweet, found the sentiment of each word.
  3. Calculated the sentiment of each tweet by taking the sum of the sentiments of its words.

Cleanning¶

I used punct_re regular expression from the previous part to clean up the text a bit more. The goal here was to remove all of the punctuations to ensure words can be properly matched with those from VADER to actually calculate the full sentiment score.

The following function sanitize_texts takes in a table df and adds a new column clean_text by converting all characters in its original full_text column to lower case and replace all instances of punctuations with a space character.

In [37]:
def sanitize_texts(df):
    df["clean_text"] = df["full_text"].str.replace(punct_re, " ").str.lower()
    return df

tweets = {handle: sanitize_texts(df) for handle, df in tweets.items()}
tweets["AOC"]["clean_text"].head()

Extraction¶

With the texts sanitized, I could now extract all the user mentions from tweets.

The following function extract_mentions takes in the full_text (not clean_text!) column from a tweets dataframe and uses mentions_re to extract all the mentions in a dataframe. The returned dataframe is:

  • single-indexed by the IDs of the tweets
  • has one row for each mention
  • has one column named mentions, which contains each mention in all lower-cased characters
In [39]:
def extract_mentions(full_texts):
    full_texts = full_texts.str.lower()
    mentions = full_texts.str.extractall(mentions_re).reset_index().rename(columns={0: "mentions"})
    return mentions[["mentions"]]

display(extract_mentions(tweets["AOC"]["full_text"]).head())

mentions = {handle: extract_mentions(df["full_text"]) for handle, df in tweets.items()}

Tidying Up the Data¶

I then converted the tweets into what's called a tidy format to make the sentiments easier to calculate. The to_tidy_format function implemented for you uses the clean_text column of each tweets dataframe to create a tidy table, which is:

  • single-indexed by the IDs of the tweets, for every word in the tweet.
  • has one column named word, which contains the individual words of each tweet.

The following function converts the table into the tidy format. Taking a look at the first 5 rows from the "tidied" tweets dataframe for AOC we can see that the structure has changed.

In [42]:
def to_tidy_format(df):
    tidy = (
        df["clean_text"]
        .str.split()
        .explode()
        .to_frame()
        .rename(columns={"clean_text": "word"})
    )
    return tidy

tidy_tweets = {handle: to_tidy_format(df) for handle, df in tweets.items()}
tidy_tweets["AOC"].head()

Adding in the Polarity Score¶

Once I had the table in the tidy format, it became much easier to find the sentiment of each tweet: I could just join the table with the lexicon table.

The following add_polarity function added a new polarity column to the df table. The polarity column contained the sum of the sentiment polarity of each word in the text of the tweet.

In [43]:
# just run this cell
def add_polarity(df, tidy_df):
    df["polarity"] = (
        tidy_df
        .merge(sent, how='left', left_on='word', right_index=True)
        .reset_index()
        .loc[:, ['id', 'polarity']]
        .fillna(0)
        .groupby('id')
        .sum()
    )
    return df

tweets = {handle: add_polarity(df, tidy_df) for (handle, df), tidy_df in \
          zip(tweets.items(), tidy_tweets.values())}
tweets["AOC"][["clean_text", "polarity"]].head()

Finally, with my polarity column in place, I could finally explore how the sentiment of each tweet related to the user(s) mentioned in it.

The function mention_polarity takes in a mentions dataframe mentions and the original tweets dataframe df and returns a series where the mentioned users are the index and the corresponding mean sentiment scores of the tweets mentioning them are the values.

In [44]:
def mention_polarity(df, mention_df):
    return mention_df.merge(df.reset_index(), left_index=True, right_index=True).groupby("mentions")["polarity"].mean()

aoc_mention_polarity = mention_polarity(tweets["AOC"],mentions["AOC"]).sort_values(ascending=False)

def polarity_by_device(original_df):
    df = pd.DataFrame()
    for key in original_df.keys():
        df[key] = original_df[key].groupby("source")["polarity"].mean()
    return df.fillna(0).reset_index()

polarity_by_device(tweets).fillna(0).reset_index()

def polarity_by_user(original_df):
    df = pd.DataFrame()
    for key in original_df.keys():
        df[key]= original_df[key]["polarity"].reset_index().drop("id", axis = 1)
    return df.mean()

Conclusion¶

For my EDA, I decided to filter the polarity of each user's tweet by the official Twitter platform's. In this way, I get a glimpse of the average polarity of each user as they are the ones who personally share something on social media.

It is interesting to observe how the means of each user differ.

This could tell us more about the type of discourse that they present.
